"""
mkt-context | Numbers | chapters 14–15
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-numbers-14-15-fill.py

Ch 14: The Kadesh-barnea rebellion — the pivotal failure of the wilderness generation.
       ANE context: collective mourning and political council; Mosaic intercession citing
       the Exod 34 formula; Hormah battle-site geography; 40-year generation math.
Ch 15: Supplemental offering laws for when Israel enters the land — graduated grain/wine
       ratios compared to Ugaritic sacrificial tariffs; firstfruits of dough (challah);
       high-handed sin category; Sabbath wood-gatherer case-law; tzitzit and tekhelet
       (the expensive murex-dye blue democratizing royalty's color).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>The congregation's corporate weeping that night responds directly to the ten faithless spies' report (ch.13). In ANE political contexts, collective public mourning was a recognized form of protest and deliberation — the Mesopotamian lament tradition (Sumerian city laments, the Lament over Destruction of Ur) shows that communal weeping before the assembly was a culturally sanctioned way to articulate collective grief and seek divine or royal intervention. The overnight weeping sets the stage for the full assembly revolt described in vv.2-4.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The grumbling (<em>vayyillonu</em>) against Moses and Aaron follows the pattern of the earlier murmuring episodes (Exod 15:24, 16:2, 17:3; Num 11:1) but intensifies: the entire congregation (<em>kol benei Yisra'el</em>, all the sons of Israel) participates. The wish 'If only we had died in Egypt or in this wilderness' is an expression of existential despair — preferring any alternative, even death, to the perceived threat ahead. This sentiment is psychologically consistent with trauma responses in enslaved populations: the known suffering of Egypt becomes preferable to the unknown dangers of freedom.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The accusation that YHWH is bringing them to die by the sword — 'our wives and children will become prey' — inverts the Exodus promise. The entire Exodus narrative was structured around YHWH's protection of Israel's children (the sparing of Israel's firstborn while Egypt's died, Exod 12:23). The cry that their children will now become the victims is a rhetorical reversal of the founding event. Historically, the fear of Canaanite military superiority was realistic: the city-states of Canaan in the Late Bronze Age were formidable fortified entities whose armies included chariotry and professional soldiers.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Let us appoint a leader and return to Egypt' — the proposal to choose a new leader (<em>netenh rosh</em>, let us appoint a head) and return to Egypt is a formal political motion, not mere venting. In ANE political discourse, proposing the installation of a new leader was a recognized challenge to existing authority, sometimes backed by formal assembly procedures. The Book of Nehemiah (9:17) later characterizes this incident as Israel's most fundamental act of covenant rejection: 'in their disobedience they appointed a leader to return to their slavery.'</p>",
    "5": "<p>Moses and Aaron fall facedown (<em>vayippelu al peneihem</em>) before the assembly — a posture of intercession, grief, or submission found across ANE contexts. In Egyptian administrative texts, falling prostrate before an authority signals either homage or entreaty; in Ugaritic poetry, the fall-to-the-ground posture accompanies intense supplication. Here it is simultaneously an act of humility before the congregation and a prayer posture before YHWH, who will respond in v10.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Joshua and Caleb tear their garments (<em>vayiqre'u begadeihem</em>) — the standard ANE and biblical expression of extreme grief, mourning, or horror (cf. Gen 37:29 when Reuben finds Joseph gone; 2 Kings 18:37 when Hezekiah's officials hear Sennacherib's blasphemy). The garment-tearing signals that Joshua and Caleb regard the people's rebellion as a catastrophe equivalent to a death — it anticipates YHWH's response in v12 where YHWH threatens to destroy the people.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The land's qualities — 'exceedingly good' (<em>tov haaretz me'od me'od</em>) — mirror the positive spy report from Num 13:27 ('it flows with milk and honey') while countering the negative conclusion the ten spies drew. Caleb and Joshua affirm the same land quality data but derive the opposite strategic conclusion: the land's goodness is a reason to go in, not a measure of what Israel will lose if they fail.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The conditional 'If the LORD is pleased with us (<em>im chafetz banu YHWH</em>)' frames the land entry as depending entirely on divine favor, not military capability. This theological framing counters the ten spies' analysis which focused exclusively on the human military balance of power. Caleb and Joshua's argument is that the decisive factor is YHWH's will, and YHWH's will has been expressed clearly: he intends to give them the land.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'They are bread for us (<em>lachmenu hem</em>)' — the phrase inverts the giants imagery of 13:33, where Israel felt like grasshoppers. 'Bread' here means easy prey, readily consumed. The claim that the Canaanites' protection has been removed — 'their shadow (<em>tsilam</em>, their covering/shade) has departed from them' — may refer to the withdrawal of divine or royal protection. In ANE imagery, the king's 'shadow' (Akkadian <em>ṣillu</em>) was the protection he extended to his subjects; when a king was defeated, his subjects were exposed. Caleb and Joshua are claiming that the Canaanites' divine-royal protection has already been withdrawn.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The attempt to stone Caleb and Joshua is halted by the appearance of YHWH's glory (<em>kevod YHWH</em>) at the tent of meeting — a divine intervention that preempts political murder. The theophanic interruption of human deliberative violence is also found in the Gideon narrative (Judg 6:34) and implicitly in the Sinai theophany (Exod 19:16-19) where divine presence silences all competing voices. YHWH's appearance at this critical juncture demonstrates that the Kadesh revolt is not merely a political dispute but a theological confrontation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH's rhetorical questions — 'How long will this people despise me? How long will they not believe me?' — frame the rebellion as unbelief (<em>emunah</em> failure) rather than mere military cowardice. This interpretation is taken up in Ps 106:24 ('they did not believe his promise') and becomes central to Hebrews' reading of the wilderness generation: their failure was theological, not logistical (Heb 3:19: 'they were unable to enter because of unbelief'). The catalog of YHWH's signs (<em>otot</em>) that Israel has witnessed — including Egypt and the wilderness — establishes the full weight of the evidence they rejected.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH's threat to disinherit Israel and start a new nation from Moses (<em>ve'e'eseh otkha legoy gadol</em>) closely parallels the golden calf incident (Exod 32:10: 'let me alone... I will make of you a great nation'). In both cases, YHWH's proposal tests Moses's intercessory character; in both cases, Moses refuses the offer and intercedes for the people. The structural parallel shows that the Kadesh rebellion is the wilderness narrative's climactic repetition of the Sinai apostasy — the second catastrophic failure whose consequences are more severe (40-year sentence vs. 3,000 deaths at the calf incident).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Moses's intercession begins with an appeal to YHWH's reputation among the nations — specifically Egypt. This is a 'what will the nations think?' argument found also in Exod 32:12 and Ezek 36:20-23. In ANE international politics, a patron deity's defeat or apparent failure to protect his people was a real concern for national prestige: Assyrian annals celebrate the gods of conquered peoples as defeated along with the people themselves. Moses is arguing from the perspective of ancient divine-reputation politics: YHWH's honor (<em>kavod</em>) is bound up with Israel's survival.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Moses's description of YHWH's presence among Israel — going before them in the cloud by day and fire by night — rehearses the Exodus theophany of Exod 13:21-22. The argument is: you have been publicly present with this people; if you now destroy them, the nations will conclude that your power was insufficient to complete what you began. The divine cloud and fire were visible to the nations (the Egyptians at least) — YHWH's visible involvement makes abandonment of Israel a public theological statement about divine ability.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The reductio ad absurdum: if YHWH kills the entire people, the nations who heard YHWH's fame will say he was unable to bring them in. The word <em>shim'ekha</em> (your fame/report) uses the same root as <em>Shema</em> — the hearing/report of YHWH's character. Moses is arguing that YHWH's word-of-mouth reputation in the international community is at stake.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The nations' anticipated verdict — 'The LORD was not able (<em>mehilti lo yukhal</em>)' — would attribute the disaster to divine impotence. This is the same accusation Egypt would make after the Exodus if YHWH abandoned Israel in the desert: the very success of the Exodus liberation would be interpreted as partial failure. Moses's argument exploits the logical structure of divine reputation in an ancient polytheistic world where deities were evaluated by the outcomes of their interventions on behalf of their peoples.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Moses pivots from diplomatic argument to direct citation of YHWH's own self-disclosure: 'Let the power of the Lord be great as you have promised.' This grounds the appeal in YHWH's own stated character rather than in Moses's advocacy — a highly sophisticated intercession strategy. By asking YHWH to act consistently with what he said about himself (Exod 34:6-7), Moses makes YHWH's integrity the ground of the appeal.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The recitation of the Exodus 34:6-7 self-description — 'the LORD is slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love, forgiving iniquity and transgression' — is the pivot of Moses's intercession. This divine self-declaration from Sinai (given to Moses after the golden calf incident, Exod 34:6-7) becomes the most quoted single passage in the OT: it is cited or alluded to in Neh 9:17, Ps 86:15, 103:8, 145:8, Joel 2:13, Jonah 4:2, Nah 1:3, and here. The recitation of YHWH's stated attributes as the basis for mercy-appeal represents a model of intercessory prayer that is unique in the ancient world — no other ANE tradition has prayer that explicitly quotes the deity's self-described character as its basis.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Moses's specific request — 'pardon the iniquity of this people according to the greatness of your steadfast love, just as you have forgiven this people from Egypt until now' — establishes Israel's entire wilderness history as a precedent for ongoing mercy. The phrase 'from Egypt until now' acknowledges the full record of Israel's failures while arguing that forgiveness has been the consistent divine response. This historical argument for mercy — past pardon as precedent for present pardon — recurs in the Psalms (Ps 44, 77, 85) and prophetic intercessions.</p>",
    "20": "<p>YHWH's response — 'I have pardoned, according to your word' (<em>salachti kidvareikha</em>) — grants the specific request Moses made (v19). The pardon is real: the people will not be instantly destroyed. But what follows is not full restoration: the judgment is redirected from immediate annihilation to generational exile. The divine forgiveness here is the forgiveness of a sovereign who can choose both to pardon the capital offense and still impose lesser consequences.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The oath formula 'As I live, and as all the earth shall be filled with the glory of the LORD' introduces the double judgment: the glory-filling of the earth is YHWH's eschatological purpose, and the wilderness generation's failure does not ultimately frustrate it — it merely removes them from participation. The glory-fills-the-earth motif appears in Isa 11:9 and Hab 2:14 as the goal of redemptive history.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The enumeration of 'ten times' (<em>aseret pe'amim</em>) Israel has tested YHWH catalogs the wilderness rebellion history. The Talmud (Arakhin 15a) and rabbinic tradition identify the ten testings precisely: two at the sea (Exod 14), two with water (Exod 15, 17), two with manna (Exod 16), one with quail (Num 11), one with the golden calf (Exod 32), one at Taberah (Num 11:1-3), and one here at Kadesh. Ten is a number of completeness — ten testings means the full measure of patience has been reached.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The exclusion of all who 'despised' YHWH from seeing the promised land. The verb <em>yena'atsuhu</em> (despised me) is strong — <em>na'ats</em> means to spurn/show contempt for (the same word used in 2 Sam 12:14 for David's contempt of YHWH's word through the Bathsheba affair). The land they had seen from Kadesh becomes the land they will never enter — their own words in v2 ('would that we had died in the wilderness') become their sentence.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Caleb's exception — 'because he has a different spirit (<em>ruach acheret</em>) and has followed me fully (<em>male' acharai</em>)' — establishes the theological basis for his survival: not military superiority but whole-hearted covenant faithfulness. The phrase <em>male' acharai</em> (literally 'filled up behind me,' following completely) becomes the formula for Caleb throughout the conquest narratives (Josh 14:8,9,14). The land Caleb reconnoitered (presumably the Hebron region, which he will inherit in Josh 14:13) is promised to him and his descendants — the specific land he reported on becomes his specific inheritance.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Amalekites and Canaanites in the valleys (Negev and Arabah) block the direct northern route to Canaan. YHWH directs Israel to turn back 'toward the wilderness by the way of the Sea of Reeds' — returning to the wilderness rather than attempting the blocked northern route. The Negev (south/dry-land region) and the Jordan valley lowlands were controlled by these peoples, making any northward advance without YHWH's presence suicidal. Archaeologically, the Late Bronze Age Negev shows evidence of semi-nomadic populations consistent with Amalekite activity.</p>",
    "26": "<p>YHWH's second address to Moses and Aaron initiates the formal sentencing oracle (vv.27-35). The dual address to both civil and priestly leadership signals that what follows is both a judicial decree and a cultic reality — the generation's exclusion from the land has both legal (covenant) and liturgical dimensions.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The grumbling (<em>telunot</em>, complaints) of this congregation is characterized as directed against YHWH himself — 'against me' (<em>alai</em>) — even though the people were complaining against Moses and Aaron (v2). This identification of complaint against human leadership with complaint against divine authority is consistent throughout Numbers: the murmuring incidents are not merely morale problems but theological transgressions. The same principle appears in 1 Sam 8:7 when Israel asks for a king: 'they have not rejected you, but they have rejected me from being king over them.'</p>",
    "28": "<p>'As I live, declares the LORD, I will do to you just what you have said in my hearing' — the lex talionis of speech: the people's words ('would that we had died in the wilderness,' v2) become their sentence. This divine irony — making the rebels' own verbal wish their fate — is a form of poetic justice found across biblical legal and prophetic texts. The self-fulfilling curse of careless speech is a recurring theme in wisdom literature (Prov 18:21: 'death and life are in the power of the tongue').</p>",
    "29": "<p>The death sentence covers all those 'registered in the census from twenty years old and upward' — precisely the military census cohort of ch.1. The two chapters now connect: the census that registered the army in ch.1 becomes, in ch.14, the register of those who will die in the wilderness. The administrative document becomes a death list.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The sole exceptions: Caleb and Joshua. Their survival as the only adults who will enter the land from the Exodus generation is remarkable — two men out of 603,550 (the ch.1 total) who will complete the journey. Historically, Caleb is identified as a Kennizite (Num 32:12), suggesting non-Israelite ancestry that was absorbed into the tribe of Judah — underscoring that faithful following of YHWH, not ethnic origin, is the decisive factor.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The reversal of the rebels' argument: they said 'our little ones will become prey' (v3); YHWH says 'your little ones shall know the land you rejected.' The very children whose vulnerability was cited as reason not to enter are the ones who will enter. The generation that refused to trust YHWH with their children's future will be replaced by those children — who will succeed where their parents failed, precisely because the parental generation is out of the way.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The parental generation's bodies will fall in the wilderness — the literal fulfillment of their own wish (v2, 'would that we had died in the wilderness'). The wilderness becomes their cemetery rather than their proving ground.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The forty-year wilderness sentence for the children: they will 'bear the weight of your faithlessness' (<em>zonu'teichem</em>, literally 'your prostitutions/faithlessnesses'). The word <em>zenut</em> (prostitution/faithlessness) is the prophetic metaphor for covenant infidelity (Hos 1-3; Jer 3; Ezek 16). The children suffer the consequence of their parents' covenant betrayal — a generational principle consistent with the 'visiting iniquity on the third and fourth generation' of Exod 20:5.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The year-for-a-day calculation: forty days of spying = forty years of wandering. This correspondence establishes a specific numeric logic for the punishment — the sentence duration mirrors the duration of the failure event. The 40-year period is confirmed in Deut 2:14 as '38 years from Kadesh-barnea to the wadi Zered' — which, added to the approximately 2 years from the Exodus to Kadesh, gives the full 40-year wilderness period. The number 40 recurs throughout the biblical wilderness tradition (Moses's 40-day fasts, Jesus's 40-day temptation) as a generation-long period of testing.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The oath formula closes the sentencing: 'I, the LORD, have spoken. Surely I will do this to all this wicked congregation gathered together (<em>haano'adim</em>, those assembled/conspired) against me.' The legal vocabulary is formal — this is a divine decree, not a threat. The word <em>no'adim</em> (assembled/conspired) connects to <em>ohel mo'ed</em> (tent of meeting, literally tent of appointed assembly) — the congregation has perverted its purpose from assembling before YHWH to assembling against him.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The ten faithless spies who brought the 'bad report' (<em>dibat ha'aretz</em>, slander/defamation of the land) die by plague immediately. The specific phrase <em>dibah</em> (malicious report/slander) is legal terminology — the spies brought a juridical slander against the land's character, analogous to bearing false witness. Their immediate death distinguishes them from the congregation, whose judgment is generational. The contrast in severity is proportional to their leadership responsibility: those who led the people astray receive immediate judgment.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The plague (<em>maggefa</em>, a sudden/striking blow) kills the ten scouts before the LORD — the location 'before the LORD' (in the tabernacle precincts) suggests a divine strike in the sacred assembly space rather than a natural epidemic. The same word <em>maggefa</em> describes the plague that followed the Baal Peor incident (25:8) — sudden divine execution in response to covenant betrayal.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Only Joshua and Caleb survive from the twelve scouts — the two who gave the faithful minority report. Their survival amid the plague that killed their ten colleagues is the first fulfillment of the distinction YHWH made between the faithful and the faithless scouts. The narrative will track their longevity through the entire forty-year period until the conquest generation enters Canaan.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Moses reports YHWH's words to the people, and 'the people mourned greatly (<em>vayitabbedu haam me'od</em>).' The grief is appropriate — they have just received their death sentence. But the grief comes too late: their mourning in vv.1-2 was for the wrong thing (fear of the future); their mourning here is for a judgment already pronounced. The sequence mirrors the pattern in prophetic literature where repentance after judgment is too late to reverse the sentence (Jer 7:16; Amos 8:12).</p>",
    "40": "<p>The presumptuous attempt to go up the next morning — 'Here we are! We will go up to the place that the LORD has said' — is an act of self-will masquerading as obedience. The people now try to do what they refused to do when commanded, without YHWH's sanction or presence. This pattern — obedience at the wrong time, in the wrong spirit, without divine commission — is condemned more severely than the original failure to obey. In ANE military terms, going to battle without the divine command or the divine presence (represented by the ark) was not bravery but presumption.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Moses's warning — 'Why are you transgressing the command of the LORD? This will not succeed' (<em>lo titslach</em>) — distinguishes between obedience and self-will. The word <em>litslach</em> (to succeed/prosper) is used throughout the OT for YHWH-directed success; its negation signals that the mission lacks divine backing. The people are attempting to reverse YHWH's decree through military action rather than through repentance and trust.</p>",
    "42": "<p>'The LORD is not among you' — the crucial military datum. In ancient Israel as in the ANE more broadly, military campaigns were understood as requiring divine presence and sanction. The Ark of the Covenant was Israel's war-palladium, accompanying the army as a sign of YHWH's presence (Num 10:35-36; 1 Sam 4:3-7). Moses warns explicitly that YHWH is not among them — without divine presence, the military venture is not merely imprudent but theologically impossible.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The Amalekites and Canaanites before them — the same peoples YHWH directed them away from in v25 — are now obstacles they presume to overcome without YHWH. The geographic reality reinforces the theological point: these enemies who blocked the route when YHWH was among them will be far more dangerous when YHWH is absent. The warning 'you shall fall by the sword' is a direct military prediction based on the absence of divine warfare support.</p>",
    "44": "<p>'But they presumed (<em>vayapilu</em>, they acted presumptuously)' to go up 'even though the ark of the LORD's covenant and Moses did not depart from the camp.' The detail about the ark's absence from the battle is theologically decisive: the ark represented YHWH's presence and war-leadership. Going to battle without the ark was going without YHWH. This detail anticipates the later catastrophe of the ark's capture (1 Sam 4-5), where Israel brought the ark to battle without divine sanction — with similar catastrophic results.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The Amalekites and Canaanites defeat Israel and drive them back to Hormah. <em>Hormah</em> (<em>cherem</em> root, meaning 'devoted to destruction/consecration') is a toponym that encodes the irony: the place whose name means 'devoted to destruction' is where Israel suffers its defeat. Later, under YHWH's sanction, Israel will return to Hormah and win decisively (Num 21:3; Josh 12:14). The same location that is defeat here becomes victory when YHWH is present — the geography encodes the theological principle.</p>"
  },
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>The speech introduction formula following immediately after ch.14's death sentence is theologically significant. The supplemental offering laws (ch.15) presuppose that Israel <em>will</em> enter the land ('when you come into the land,' v2) — a statement of hope immediately after the Kadesh judgment. This juxtaposition is deliberate: even as YHWH sentences the current generation, he speaks to the next generation about their future in the land. The law is addressed to those who will enter, not those who will die in the wilderness.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'When you come into the land you are to inhabit, which I am giving you' — the conditional framing assumes successful settlement. Laws 'when you come into the land' are a distinct genre in the Pentateuch, given in anticipation of conditions that will exist only after the conquest (cf. Deut 12:1ff). Their placement here, after the Kadesh judgment, may serve to reorient Israel's attention from the closed door of the immediate past toward the open door of the distant future — the land promise is still operative for the next generation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The category of fire offerings (<em>isheh</em>) offered 'as a burnt offering, or to fulfill a vow, or as a freewill offering, or at your appointed festivals' encompasses the full range of voluntary and obligatory sacrifices. The inclusion of freewill offerings (<em>nedavah</em>) alongside vow-fulfillment offerings and festival sacrifices shows that supplemental grain and wine provisions apply across all sacrifice types, not just the mandatory ones. The ANE context: Ugaritic ritual texts (KTU 1.40, 1.119) contain similar graduated sacrifice lists specifying grain and oil proportions by animal type, and the Ugaritic sacrificial tariff structure parallels the Numbers 15 formulas closely.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The grain offering proportions for a lamb: one-tenth of an ephah (<em>isaron</em>) of fine flour mixed with one-quarter of a hin of oil, plus a quarter-hin of wine for the drink offering. These specific volumetric measures (isaron, hin) are standardized Levitical units. An ephah was approximately 22 liters; a hin was approximately 3.7 liters. The standardization of these proportions across all sacrificial occasions ensures consistency in the sanctuary's cultic economy regardless of which festival or offering type is being observed.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A quarter-hin of wine for the drink offering accompanying the lamb. The inclusion of wine in the sacrificial system is noteworthy: wine was among the most valuable agricultural products in the ancient Levant, and wine offerings to deities are well-attested in Canaanite (Ugaritic), Egyptian, and Mesopotamian cult. The Israelite drink offering (<em>nesekh</em>) is probably derived from the wider ANE practice of libation offerings poured out before or upon the altar.</p>",
    "6": "<p>For a ram: two-tenths of an ephah of flour with one-third of a hin of oil. The graduated scale (larger animal = larger grain accompaniment) mirrors the economic logic of the graduated chatat scale (Lev 5:6-11) and reflects a general ANE principle that offerings should be proportional to the value of the main sacrifice. Ugaritic sacrificial tariffs (RS 24.643) contain similar graduated grain proportions for different animal classes.</p>",
    "7": "<p>One-third of a hin of wine for a ram. The drink offering quantity scales proportionally with the flour and oil measures — maintaining consistent ratios across animal sizes. This mathematical proportionality is a hallmark of priestly legislation in the Pentateuch and reflects the administrative sophistication of the Levitical system.</p>",
    "8": "<p>For a bull (the largest standard sacrificial animal): three-tenths of an ephah of flour with half a hin of oil. The tripling of the minimum quantity (3/10 vs. 1/10 for a lamb) for the largest animal maintains the proportional structure. Bulls were the most expensive sacrificial animals and were used primarily in the most significant offerings (burnt offerings, sin offerings, dedication ceremonies), so the larger grain-accompaniment investment was appropriate.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Three-tenths of an ephah of fine flour with half a hin of oil — the full grain offering accompanying a bull. The precision of these measures in the priestly legislation is consistent with what we know of ancient temple economies: Mesopotamian temple archives (especially from Ur III and neo-Babylonian periods) kept meticulous records of grain, oil, and wine allocations for cultic use, down to fractional measures.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Half a hin of wine for a bull. The complete scale — lamb (1/4 hin), ram (1/3 hin), bull (1/2 hin) — creates a proportional structure that can be memorized and applied consistently. The pleasing aroma (<em>rei'ach nicho'ach</em>) formula that closes the wine offering instructions is the standard descriptor for sacrifices accepted by YHWH, used over 40 times in the Pentateuch.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'This shall be done for each bull, each ram, and each lamb or goat.' The universal application clause ensures the supplemental offering system applies regardless of the sacrifice's purpose — there is no category of animal offering that bypasses the grain-oil-wine accompaniment requirement.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Proportional scaling for multiple animals: whatever the number, each animal receives its proportional grain offering. The clause ensures that a person offering ten rams does not bring ten times the single-ram measure — each individual offering maintains its complete grain accompaniment. This individualization of the supplemental offerings prevents either under-providing or over-providing for the sanctuary stores.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Every native Israelite shall follow this procedure' — the term <em>ezrach</em> (native/citizen, literally 'one who grows here,' from <em>zarach</em>, to rise/grow) is the standard term for the indigenous Israelite in legal contexts. The specification of native Israelite procedure before extending it to resident aliens (v14) establishes the baseline law that will then be universalized.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The extension to resident aliens (<em>ger</em>) who present offerings — they follow the same procedure as native Israelites. The <em>ger</em> (sojourner/resident alien) was a significant social category in ancient Israel — a non-Israelite who lived within the community without full tribal membership. The Pentateuch consistently extends religious and civil protections to the ger (Exod 12:48-49; Lev 19:33-34), and here the extension covers cultic participation: the ger who wishes to offer sacrifices does so by the same rules as a native citizen.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'One statute for the congregation (<em>chukkat olam</em>, permanent statute) — for you and for the resident alien' — the universalization principle. No second-class liturgical participation for resident aliens: the same rules, the same grain offerings, the same proportions. The phrase <em>chukkat olam</em> (permanent statute) signals this is not a temporary accommodation but a permanent feature of the covenant community's structure. This inclusion of non-Israelites under the same sacrificial law anticipates the NT's breaking down of the Jew/Gentile distinction in worship (Eph 2:14-16).</p>",
    "16": "<p>'One law and one rule (<em>mishpat echad</em>) shall apply to both you and the resident alien.' The restatement emphasizes the legal equality in cultic matters — not just a pious aspiration but a statutory requirement. The <em>mishpat</em> (law/judgment/rule) vocabulary makes this a legal, not merely ethical, equality.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A new divine speech introducing the firstfruits-of-dough law (vv.18-21). The separate speech introduction signals a distinct legal unit from the grain-offering proportions of vv.3-16.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'When you come into the land to which I am bringing you' — the land-entry framing recurs from v2, reinforcing the forward-looking orientation of ch.15 as legislation for the next generation. The firstfruits laws are all grounded in the agricultural economy that Israel will have in the land — the wilderness has no such economy.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The firstfruits contribution (<em>terumah</em>) from the land's produce is the general principle: 'you shall present a contribution (<em>terumah</em>) as a gift to the LORD.' The <em>terumah</em> (heave offering/contribution) is lifted up (<em>rum</em>) as a dedication to YHWH's portion — it is distinguished from the tithe and the firstfruits in technical detail but shares the principle of the land's yield belonging first to YHWH.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'From the first of your dough (<em>reshit arisotekhem</em>) you shall present a loaf as a contribution.' The firstfruits of the bread-making process — specifically the first batch of dough prepared from the new grain — was to be offered before the household consumed any. This law is the basis for the Jewish practice of <em>challah</em> (taking a portion of dough before baking, which Jews still practice today as a remembrance of this command). The specific focus on processed grain (dough rather than raw grain) distinguishes this from the harvest firstfruits laws elsewhere.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Throughout your generations' (<em>ledoroteichem</em>) — the challah-dough offering is a permanent generational obligation, not limited to the first harvest. The continuity of the obligation across generations serves as a repeated acknowledgment that the land and its produce belong ultimately to YHWH, who gave it to Israel as a gift.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The unintentional sin provisions begin: 'But if you sin unintentionally (<em>bishegagah</em>) and do not observe all these commandments.' The category of <em>shegagah</em> (unintentional/inadvertent sin, literally 'erring/straying') is distinct from the high-handed sin of v30. The difference is moral awareness: unintentional sins are committed without full awareness of their transgression; high-handed sins are committed with deliberate defiance.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The scope of the unintentional sin provision covers 'all that the LORD commanded through Moses from the day the LORD gave the command and onward throughout your generations' — the entire Mosaic corpus, not just the supplemental offerings of this chapter. The provision applies to inadvertent violations of any commandment in any generation.</p>",
    "24": "<p>If the unintentional sin was committed by the congregation as a whole without their knowledge, the atonement requires a bull as burnt offering with its grain/drink accompaniments, plus a goat as sin offering — the standard communal sin offering package. The combination of an <em>'olah</em> (expressing dedication) and a <em>chattat</em> (expressing purification) addresses both the need for renewed consecration and the need for cleansing from inadvertent ritual transgression.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The priest makes atonement for the whole congregation, and they 'shall be forgiven, for it was unintentional (<em>shegagah</em>).' The causal connection between the sacrifice's performance and the forgiveness is direct: <em>venislach lahem</em> (and they shall be forgiven). The Levitical atonement system is presented as reliably effective for inadvertent sins — the mechanism functions as designed when the categories are correctly applied.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The forgiveness extends to 'the resident alien living among them' — the same universalization seen in vv.15-16. The communal atonement covers the entire resident population, not just native Israelites. This means the ger shares both the cultic obligation (v13-14) and the cultic benefit (forgiveness) of the congregational atonement system.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The individual (rather than congregational) unintentional sin offering: one yearling female goat (<em>seir izzim bat shenata</em>). The provision of an individual offering for inadvertent sin parallels the graduated chatat of Lev 5:1-13 (which includes poverty provisions). The fact that ch.15 does not include poverty provisions suggests this is a supplemental specification, not a replacement of the Lev 5 system.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The priest makes atonement for the individual, 'making atonement before the LORD for the person who sinned' — and the person 'shall be forgiven.' The formula is identical to v25's communal atonement — same mechanism, same result, scaled to an individual. The priestly mediation system is designed to handle both corporate and individual sin under the same theological framework.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'You shall have one law for the person who acts unintentionally, whether native-born among the Israelites or a resident alien.' The universalization formula applied to individual atonement: whether Israelite or ger, the procedure and the forgiveness are identical. This legal equality in atonement access is notable — in ANE temple systems, access to priestly atonement was typically restricted to citizens of the city or nation, not to resident foreigners.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'But the person who acts defiantly (<em>beyad ramah</em>, literally with a raised hand)' — the high-handed sin category. The raised-hand gesture is a posture of defiance or challenge in both ancient and modern idiom. This person 'blasphemes the LORD' (<em>megadef et YHWH</em>) — the deliberate, knowing transgression of a divine command is treated as an act of contempt for YHWH's authority rather than mere inadvertence. The death sentence (v35) and cutting off from the people (<em>nikretah</em>, karet) apply to this category. There is no sacrificial remedy for high-handed sin in the Levitical system.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'Because he has despised the word of the LORD (<em>ki devar YHWH bazah</em>)' — the precise characterization: high-handed sin is the despising (<em>bazah</em>, to hold in contempt) of YHWH's word. This root appears in Saul's sin (1 Sam 15:9, when he spares Agag: YHWH says Saul has rejected YHWH's word) and David's sin (2 Sam 12:9-10: 'You have despised the word of the LORD'). The karet penalty (being 'cut off' from the people) is the covenant sanction that removes the sinner from the community — whether by human execution, premature death, or childlessness is debated, but the effect is exclusion from Israel's covenant life and legacy.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The Sabbath wood-gatherer case immediately follows the high-handed sin legislation as an illustration. The placement is interpretively significant: the case was apparently debated as to whether it was inadvertent or high-handed. The man is 'found' (<em>vayimtse'u</em>) gathering wood — the Hebrew suggests he was caught in the act by community members, not that he reported himself. The Sabbath prohibition on labor was one of the most fundamental covenant obligations, explicitly carrying the death penalty (Exod 31:14-15; 35:2).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The wood-gatherer is brought before Moses, Aaron, and the whole congregation. The formal assembly of the community for the legal case follows the pattern of communal judicial procedure in the ancient Levant: cases involving capital punishment required the full community's deliberation and execution. The bringing of the case to Moses and Aaron reflects the still-developing state of Israel's legal system — not every application of divine law had been worked out in advance.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'They put him in custody because it had not been made clear (<em>lo forash</em>) what should be done to him.' This remarkable admission of legal uncertainty in the narrative acknowledges that not every case was pre-adjudicated by the existing laws. The technical vocabulary <em>lo forash</em> (had not been specified/declared) is a legal term for a gap in existing legislation — a lacuna that requires divine clarification. This consultation mechanism (detaining until YHWH speaks) parallels the later use of Urim and Thummim for legal uncertainty (Num 27:21).</p>",
    "35": "<p>YHWH's clarification: the death penalty, executed by stoning outside the camp with the whole congregation participating. The outside-the-camp execution location reflects the same logic as the burning of sin offering remains outside the camp (Lev 4:12,21) — what is under divine judgment or laden with impurity must be removed from the sacred space of the covenant community. The communal execution ('the whole congregation shall stone him') distributes the responsibility across the entire community, preventing the emergence of an executioner class and ensuring corporate accountability for covenant enforcement.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The congregation executes the sentence exactly as commanded. The compliance formula ('as the LORD commanded Moses') confirms that the wood-gatherer incident is a case-law illustration of the high-handed sin principle: gathering wood on the Sabbath was deliberately defiant, not inadvertent. The incident thus closes the gap created by vv.30-31 — the abstract principle now has a concrete, narrated application.</p>",
    "37": "<p>A new divine speech introduces the tzitzit (fringe/tassel) law. The placement of the tzitzit command at the end of ch.15 — after the inadvertent-sin provision, the high-handed-sin ruling, and the wood-gatherer case — is pedagogically significant: the tzitzit are introduced as a memory device to prevent both inadvertent sin (by reminding one of all the commandments) and high-handed sin (by keeping the commandments constantly before one's eyes).</p>",
    "38": "<p>The tzitzit command: tassels on the corners (<em>kanfei vegadeihem</em>, the wings/corners of their garments) with a blue cord (<em>ptil tekhelet</em>). The <em>tekhelet</em> blue was made from the hyacinth murex snail (<em>Hexaplex trunculus</em>, or possibly <em>Murex brandaris</em>) found on the Mediterranean coast. The dyeing process was expensive and time-consuming — the same dye used for royal and priestly garments across the ancient world. The blue color was associated with divinity and royalty in Egypt (pharaonic blue), Mesopotamia (lapis lazuli as divine color), and Ugarit (divine garments described as blue). The command to put blue on every Israelite's garment democratizes a color previously restricted to the elite — every covenant member wears the royal/divine color as a mark of their status before YHWH.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'The tassels shall be for you to look at, so that you may remember all the LORD's commandments.' The tzitzit function as a visual mnemonic — a covenant memory device worn on the body. This is comparable to other ancient mnemonic and apotropaic practices: Egyptian <em>menat</em> necklaces, Mesopotamian amulets inscribed with divine names, and Israelite tefillin (phylacteries) all serve the function of keeping the wearer in relation to the sacred. The rabbinic tradition counts the numerical value of <em>tzitzit</em> (600) plus 8 threads plus 5 knots = 613, corresponding to the traditional count of Torah commandments — the entire Torah encoded in the garment's fringe. The danger being addressed is 'not following your own heart and eyes' (<em>lo taturu</em>) — independent moral reasoning that strays from the covenant.</p>",
    "40": "<p>'So you shall remember and do all my commandments, and you shall be holy to your God.' The tzitzit law closes with the holiness imperative that opened the Holiness Code (Lev 19:2). The connection between remembering-doing and being holy is direct: the tzitzit are a behavioral reminder system whose purpose is covenant fidelity, whose goal is holiness. The visual cue → memory → action → holiness chain summarizes the pedagogical logic of the command.</p>",
    "41": "<p>'I am the LORD your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt to be your God.' The chapter closes with the foundational self-identification formula — the same formula that opens the Ten Commandments (Exod 20:2). The tzitzit law and the entire supplemental legislation of ch.15 are grounded in and conclude with the Exodus-identity statement: YHWH's authority to command is inseparable from his identity as Israel's Redeemer. The 'I am the LORD your God' formula grounds every subsequent obligation in the prior act of redemptive grace — the imperative always rests upon the indicative of divine deliverance.</p>"
  }
}

